        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i>The ruling coalition needed 50 seats to retain control of the 248-seat upper chamber. It ended up with 47. Credits: NYT</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          <strong>The what:</strong> Japanese PM Shigeru Ishiba‚Äôs coalition headed to the polls as control over half of the 248-seat upper chamber was at stake. They <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-21-jul-25-spotlight-h1-1-lost-their-majority" target="_blank">lost their majority</a> as people were frustrated over the rising expenses and the threat of US tariffs. Speaking after the results, Ishiba said that he solemnly accepts the harsh result, but intends to remain in position. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
        <strong>The background:</strong> The rise of the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-21-jul-25-spotlight-h1-2-far-right-sanseito-party" target="_blank">far-right Sanseito party</a> and their ‚ÄúJapanese First‚Äù campaign has struck a chord with voters. They use anti-immigration propaganda, tax cut assertions, and conspiracy theories to sway public support. Ishiba‚Äôs coalition has failed to address the rising number of tourists and foreign immigrants, who are often found to disrespect Japan‚Äôs conservative ecosystem. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
       <strong>The big picture:</strong> This loss follows their poor showing in the lower house <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-21-jul-25-spotlight-h1-3-election-in-october-2024" target="_blank">election in October 2024</a>. Analysts predict that the loss would result in a potential shift in leadership, potentially leading to political turmoil and economic instability. The <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-21-jul-25-spotlight-h1-4-yen-has-strengthened" target="_blank">yen has strengthened</a> on global markets as investors expected this result.
          </p>
      
