            ">Belarus' political power play</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>Summary: The release of political prisoners by Belarus raises questions about its intent to cooperate with the West. </strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          <strong>The what:</strong> Belarus recently released the opposition leader Siarhei Tsikhanouski and five other Belarusian political prisoners. Their release is seen as a <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-21-jul-25-analysis-h1-8-tactical-move" target="_blank">tactical move</a>, as Belarus aims to secure sanction relief while maintaining its ties with the Kremlin. For the US, the release is another victory in its hostage diplomacy. But analysts suggest that the US should not mistake signals for shifts.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          <strong>The background:</strong> Once the leader of the global potash market, Belarus‚Äôs global market share dropped from 20% to just under 10%, with exports routed through Russia. The release of Tsikhanouski is also seen as a triumph of the repressed democratic uprising. Belarus still reels from the unresolved trauma of the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-21-jul-25-analysis-h1-9-2020-repression" target="_blank">2020 repression</a>, while being repressive than Russia. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         <strong>What‚Äôs next:</strong> The EU said the sanctions will not be lifted till the full release of 1,200 political prisoners, and a demonstrable end to repression. Analysts suggest setting out conditions for gradual relief, accompanied by verifiable benchmarks, including snapback provisions in case repression resumes. Critics argue that Belarus is not undergoing reform, but rather negotiating. 
          </p>
