        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">What is sportswashing? </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/understanding-sportswashing-democracy-vs-autocratic-influence.jpg" alt="Only by understanding the mechanics of sportswashing can democratic actors recognize, prioritize, and counter this emerging and disruptive form of autocratic influence" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i>By understanding the mechanics of sportswashing can democratic actors recognize, prioritize, and counter this emerging and disruptive way of autocratic influence. Credits: FIFA</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          <strong>The what:</strong> Sportswashing refers to the use of sports to enhance a country‚Äôs image, often to <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-21-jul-25-foundations-h1-15-distract-from" target="_blank">distract from</a> its human rights abuses or political issues. The term was first put to use in 2015 to describe Azerbaijan‚Äôs actions during the European Games in Baku to deflect criticism concerning its ongoing repression within the country. Recent examples include the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-21-jul-25-foundations-h1-16-2022-fifa-world-cup" target="_blank">2022 FIFA World Cup</a> and the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-21-jul-25-foundations-h1-17-2022-winter-olympics" target="_blank">2022 Winter Olympics</a> in Beijing.  
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
       <strong>The why:</strong> Sports can be used as a powerful tool for political messaging and soft power. The UN and other international development agencies have utilized sport to empower women and girls, combat discrimination, and foster peace. However, some countries invest in global sports as a means of reputation laundering, distracting attention from human rights issues and boosting their international influence. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
        <strong>The criticism:</strong> Critics assert that those opposed to sportswashing primarily focus on non-Western nations and overlook Western nations' atrocities. It also undermines the genuine economic diversification, genuine interest in sports, or tourism development efforts. The overutilization of the term also threatens the spirit of sport by turning every sports event into a political battleground.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
